iYes, you read that right. Without the need for Faraday cages or		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
isignal-blocking measures, you can build a legal LTE network at home		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i(in the US) for around $100, capable of transmitting continuously		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i24/7.		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i> Regarding "legal": I am not a lawyer or a wireless expert. Based		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
ion my research into the relevant policies and regulations, my entire		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
isetup should be legal. However, I take no responsibility if you		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iencounter any legal issues after following the instructions in this		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
ipost.		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iCBRS Band: Unlicensed LTE/5G Band in the US		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iThe challenge in building your own LTE network lies not in the		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
itechnology but in legally acquiring radio spectrum resources. On the		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
isoftware side, as early as 2014, solutions like		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
hsrsRAN	URL:https://www.srslte.com/	{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
ibased on SDR (Software Defined Radio) for LTE transmission were		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iavailable, along with open-source core network software like		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
hMagma	URL:https://magmacore.org/	{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iand		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
hOpen5GS	URL:https://open5gs.org/	{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iHowever, when it comes to radio spectrum, the frequencies used by LTE		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iand 5G mobile networks fall within licensed bands. To use them		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
ilegally, you must apply to the local radio regulatory authority and		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
ipay expensive spectrum usage fees (usually based on coverage area and		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
ilocal population). Unless you live in a sparsely populated area, most		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
ienthusiasts will be stopped at this step. If you transmit without		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iauthorization, you will interfere with operators using the same		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
ifrequency, and the affected operators have a strong incentive to		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
icollaborate with enforcement agencies to locate the source of		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iinterference and heavily fine you.		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iIn 2017, however, the Federal Communications Commission (FCC) opened		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
ithe 3550-3700 MHz band to the public, known as the CBRS (Citizens		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iBroadband Radio Service) band. Anyone who meets simple restrictions		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
ican transmit on this band without prior authorization. Since this band		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
icorresponds to LTE band 48 and 5G band n48, you can transmit LTE or 5G		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
isignals on this band, allowing phones that support band 48 to connect,		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
ithereby legally establishing your own LTE/5G network.		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iIf many devices transmit on the same band without coordination, severe		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
isignal interference will occur, rendering the band unusable for		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
ieveryone. To address this, CBRS introduced the SAS system (Spectrum		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iAccess System) to manage all radio devices transmitting on the CBRS		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iband. SAS categorizes CBRS users into three levels:		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i- Incumbent Access: Users who were authorized to use this band before		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i2017 have the highest priority. These are typically satellite control		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
istations and US Navy radars. If these users transmit on the CBRS band,		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iall other users must yield.		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i- Priority Access: Users who have obtained priority usage rights for		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iportions of the CBRS band through auctions have a lower priority than		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iincumbent users but higher than all other users.		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i- General Authorized Access: All other users without prior		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iauthorization have the lowest priority and must yield to all other		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iusers.		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iAll CBRS band users, except the US Navy, must obtain authorization		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
ifrom SAS before starting transmission, allowing SAS to dynamically		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iadjust frequency allocations in different areas to prevent mutual		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iinterference. For interference from US Navy radars, SAS uses signal		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
ireceivers installed along the US coast to determine if the US Navy is		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iusing the band.		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iTherefore, with a LTE/5G base station that supports the CBRS band and		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
ican connect to SAS to obtain frequency allocations, you can legally		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
itransmit signals and build your own mobile network.		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iBut where can you buy such a device?		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iBuying a Used Base Station on eBay		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iAfter the CBRS band was opened, it attracted the interest of many		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
icompanies.		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
hAs of today, 95 companies have joined the CBRS Alliance	URL:https://ongoalliance.org/members/	{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i, including the big three US operators AT&T, T-Mobile, and Verizon,		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iSAS system operators Google and Federated Wireless, and base station		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iequipment manufacturers Baicells and Sercomm, among others.		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iAnother company called Nova Labs was also interested in CBRS. Nova		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iLabs operates a virtual network operator (MVNO) called Helium Mobile,		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iproviding services through T-Mobile's mobile network. To achieve lower		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
icosts and lower plan prices than other virtual operators, they:		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i- Sold Wi-Fi hotspots and CBRS base stations dedicated to the Helium		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iMobile network, allowing users to share their existing broadband		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iconnection.		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i- Prioritized Helium Mobile users to use these Wi-Fi hotspots and CBRS		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
ibase stations, bypassing T-Mobile to reduce data traffic costs.		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i- Issued a digital currency called HNT, and used HNT to pay for		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
itraffic cost on Wi-Fi hotspots and CBRS base stations.		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iHowever, Nova Labs could never solve the stability issues of roaming		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
ito CBRS base stations and eventually abandoned the CBRS network		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
ientirely in March 2025, fully transitioning to using Wi-Fi hotspots.		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iThe CBRS base stations, originally costing thousands of dollars, were		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
ireplaced and now listed on eBay for around $60 each. After flashing		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iback to the original firmware and unlocking the management interface,		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
ithese base stations can connect to core networks built with Magma,		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iOpen5GS, etc., and transmit for your own LTE network.		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
hSearch for "CBRS" on eBay	URL:https://www.ebay.com/sch/i.html?_nkw=cbrs&_sacat=0&_sop=15	{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
ito find many CBRS base stations from the Helium Mobile network.		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iNote that Helium Mobile sells two types of CBRS base stations:		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i- Indoor base stations produced by Sercomm, branded by FreedomFi or		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iMosoLabs, model `SCE4255W`, characterized by the FreedomFi or MosoLabs		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
ilogo on the casing.		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
IFreedomFi/Sercomm Indoor Base Station Appearance	/usr/uploads/202504/cbrs-indoor-radio.jpg	{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i(Image source: Amazon)		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i- Outdoor base stations produced by Baicells, model `Nova 430h`,		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
icharacterized by the orange Baicells logo on the casing.		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
IBaicells Outdoor Base Station Appearance	/usr/uploads/202504/cbrs-outdoor-radio.jpg	{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i(Image source: Amazon)		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iIf you are deploying at home,		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iyou must buy an indoor base station		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i, not an outdoor one. The differences between the two are:		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i- Indoor base stations can only be used indoors. They can easily		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iconnect to SAS without additional steps.		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i- Outdoor base stations can only be used outdoors. They have higher		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iSAS authorization fees, and require a CBRS Alliance-authorized		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iinstaller to check the installation before transmission can begin. If		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iyou want to install an outdoor base station but can't find an		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iauthorized installer,		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
hyou can also spend $600 to get certified as an authorized installer	URL:https://www.coursera.org/learn/google-cbrs-cpi-training	{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i, valid for 3 years, and then you can approve your own base stations		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iand install as many base stations as you want.		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iI didn't want to spend $600 on a certification that has little other		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iuse, so I bought an indoor base station directly.		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iUnlocking the Management Interface of the Indoor Base Station		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iWhen you buy a FreedomFi/Sercomm SCE4255W indoor base station from		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
ieBay, plug it in and turn it on, you'll find you can't connect to the		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
ibase station's web management interface to change its configuration.		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iThis was done to prevent base station owners from messing with the		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
isettings, which could affect network stability, but it also prevents		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
ius from using the base station elsewhere.		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iHowever, these base stations connect to a central server to get		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iconfigurations via the HTTP-based TR-069 protocol, a term you might be		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
ifamiliar with if you've ever modified your model or router provided by		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iISP. We can hijack the default control server address to our own		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
icontrol server, allowing us to freely modify the base station's		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iconfiguration.		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iIf you plan to use Magma to build your core network, you can skip this		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
istep. Magma comes with a TR-069 server that can send configurations to		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
ithe base station, and engineers from Helium Mobile and FreedomFi have		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
ialready added support for this base station to Magma, so we can later		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
ihijack the base station's control server `acs.freedomfi.com` to Magma		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
ivia DNS.		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iIf you plan to use Open5GS or other software that doesn't support		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iTR-069 to build your core network, you can use my script to simulate a		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iTR-069 server and send the command to enable the web management		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iinterface to the base station:		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i- Download the `tr069.py` script from		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
hhttps://github.com/xddxdd/freedomfi-cbrs-enable-webui	URL:https://github.com/xddxdd/freedomfi-cbrs-enable-webui	{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i- Install Python 3, then run `python3 tr069.py`.		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i- Modify your router's DNS settings to hijack the IP of		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i`acs.freedomfi.com` to the IP of the computer running the `tr069.py`		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iscript. My router uses OpenWRT, so I can add a rule in the Dnsmasq		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iconfiguration page: `/acs.freedomfi.com/192.168.4.2`.		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i- Unbox the base station, connect it with an Ethernet cable, and plug		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iin the power.		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i- Wait a moment, and you should see a large amount of XML output in		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
ithe window running the `tr069.py` script, which are the commands sent		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iby the base station to the server. If you aren't receiving any		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
irequests, check if the DNS configuration is correct and if there's a		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
ifirewall on your computer blocking port 8443.		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i- When you see output containing `cwmp:SetParameterValuesResponse`, it		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
imeans the web management interface has been successfully enabled. The		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
icomplete output should look like this:		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iAfter enabling the management interface, you can access the base		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
istation's management interface via HTTPS, like		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i`https://192.168.1.123/`.		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
IIndoor Base Station Login Interface	/usr/uploads/202504/sercomm-login.png	{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iThe default username and password are `sc_femto` and `tsFid2wz` (from		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iHelium Mobile's Discord:		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
hlink	URL:https://discord.com/channels/404106811252408320/836735476659912754/1355330850232995861	{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
IIndoor Base Station Management Interface	/usr/uploads/202504/sercomm-status.png	{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iPurchasing Programmable SIM Cards		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iAfter building your LTE network, you'll need some SIM cards with your		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
inetwork's configuration programmed on them to allow phones to connect		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
ito your network. Since the information on regular SIM cards is		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
ihardcoded during production, you can't just buy any SIM card; you must		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iuse programmable SIM cards.		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iSearch for `Programmable SIM` on shopping websites like Amazon and		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iAliexpress to find these cards, for example:		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
hhttps://www.amazon.com/s?k=Programmable+SIM	URL:https://www.amazon.com/s?k=Programmable+SIM	{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
IProgrammable SIM Card Appearance	/usr/uploads/202504/programmable-sim-card.jpg	{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i(Image source: Amazon)		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iI bought a set of SIM cards on Amazon for $38.99, which included 5		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iprogrammable SIM cards, a card programmer, a USB drive with Windows		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
icard-programming software, and an adapter from Micro SIM/Nano SIM to		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
ifull-size SIM.		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iBuilding a Magma Core Network		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iTo build your own LTE network, you first need a core network. The LTE		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
icore network mainly manages user device (e.g., phone) authentication		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iinformation and controls billing, traffic throttling, and other		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
ifunctions.		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iMagma is an open-source 4G/5G core network developed by Meta		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i(Facebook), running on Docker/Kubernetes. It can quickly scale		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
ihorizontally to support large amounts of mobile network traffic and		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
ican run on low-spec devices like Raspberry Pi to provide simple		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
inetwork services.		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iSince I don't need the complex container orchestration features of		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iKubernetes, I chose to build Magma's components using Docker.		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i> I referenced the following materials during the configuration		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iprocess:		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i- Core network (Orchestrator and NMS) part:		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
h[Study Note] How To Install Magma Core (Orchestrator)	URL:https://hackmd.io/@RaffieWinata/rJ5oHgk3a#1-Install-Orchestrator-and-NMS	{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i- Core network (Orchestrator and NMS) part:		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
hHow To Configure Magma Orchestrator & NMS - RakWireless	URL:https://learn.rakwireless.com/hc/en-us/articles/26476385758615-How-To-Configure-Magma-Orchestrator-NMS	{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i- Access Gateway part:		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
hInstall Docker-based Access Gateway on Ubuntu - Magma	URL:https://magma.github.io/magma/docs/lte/deploy_install_docker	{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iBuilding the Magma Core Network (Orchestrator and NMS)		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iFirst, prepare a system to run the core network. I chose to create a		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
ivirtual machine on Proxmox VE. After installation, the system services		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iand Magma together use about 4GB of memory, so a virtual machine with		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iabout 8GB of memory should be sufficient.		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iI installed Ubuntu 24.04, but other systems should theoretically work		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
ias well.		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iThen, install Docker and Docker-compose.		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iThen, execute the following operations:		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iThen, in your local browser, visit		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
hhttps://magma-test.magma.test	URL:https://magma-test.magma.test	{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i(or `magma-test.[your own domain]`), and you should see the login		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iinterface. If you see an address not found error, confirm that the		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
idomain is resolving correctly.		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
IMagma Login Interface	/usr/uploads/202504/magma-login.png	{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iLog in with the default username `admin@magma.test` and password		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i`password1234`.		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iIn the left `Network` tab, add a network and fill in the following:		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i- In the `Config` tab, `Network ID` and `Network Name` can be filled		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iin arbitrarily.		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
IMagma Add Network Interface	/usr/uploads/202504/magma-add-network.png	{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i- In the `Epc` tab, change MCC to `315`, MNC to `010`, and TAC to `1`.		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iMCC/MNC are the codes for mobile operators, for example, AT&T's		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iMCC/MNC is `310/410`, and T-Mobile's is `310/260`. `315/010` is the		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
icode specifically allocated for CBRS networks, and all mobile networks		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
ion the CBRS band can use it.		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
IMagma Add Network Interface Epc Tab	/usr/uploads/202504/magma-add-network-epc.png	{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i- In the `Ran` tab, change `Bandwidth` to 20 MHz for the fastest		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
ispeed. Select `Band Type` as `TDD` because the LTE 48/5G n48 band uses		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iTDD time-division multiplexing.		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i- Fill in EARFCNDL with `55540`, which represents the 3580 MHz		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
ifrequency point within the CBRS band, but the CBRS base station will		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iactually use the frequency allocated by SAS, not the one specified		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
ihere.		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i- Keep all other configurations at their defaults.		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
IMagma Add Network Interface Ran Tab	/usr/uploads/202504/magma-add-network-ran.png	{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iAfter completing the above configuration, you now have an LTE core		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
inetwork. However, your base station cannot directly connect to the		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
icore network; it needs another component: the Access Gateway (AGW).		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iBuilding the Magma Access Gateway (AGW)		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iMagma's Access Gateway manages the base station and forwards the base		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
istation's data traffic to the internet. Note that Magma's core network		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
ionly manages user information and does not handle data traffic, and		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
ithe traffic from the Access Gateway does not pass through the core		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
inetwork.		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iFirst, prepare a system to run the Access Gateway. This system needs		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
ito be configured with two network interfaces, where `eth0` is used for		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iremote management and connecting to the core network, and `eth1` is		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iused for connecting to the base station. If you're using a separate		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
icomputer, you'll need to plug the base station's Ethernet cable into		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
ithe `eth1` interface later, and Magma will automatically configure		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iDHCP to allow the base station to connect to the Access Gateway.		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iHowever, since I'm using a virtual machine on Proxmox VE, I chose to		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iplace the additional `eth1` interface in a VLAN and set up the		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
icorresponding VLAN and IP on the main router. This way, I can ping the		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i`eth1` IP from any machine on my local network, meaning the base		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
istation can be plugged into any port on my main switch.		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iThis system must be installed with Ubuntu 20.04 because the Magma		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iAccess Gateway installation modifies many system configurations, and		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
ithese modifications are only supported on Ubuntu 20.04.		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iAfter installation, the system services and Magma together use about		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i1GB of memory, so a virtual machine with about 2-4GB of memory should		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
ibe sufficient.		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iThen, install Docker and Docker-compose.		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iThen, execute the following operations:		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iReturn to the core network management interface at		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
hhttps://magma-test.magma.test	URL:https://magma-test.magma.test	{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i(or `magma-test.[your own domain]`), go to the left `Equipment` tab,		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iand ensure the network you created earlier is selected in the top		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iright corner.		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iClick the `Add New` button in the top right to add the Access Gateway,		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iand fill in the following:		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i- In the `Config` tab, `Gateway Name` and `Gateway ID` can be filled		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iin arbitrarily.		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i- In the `Config` tab, fill in `Hardware UUID` with the `Hardware ID`		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iyou obtained from the Access Gateway.		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i- In the `Config` tab, fill in `Challenge Key` with the `Challenge		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
ikey` you obtained from the Access Gateway.		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i- Keep all other configurations at their defaults.		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
IMagma Add Access Gateway Interface	/usr/uploads/202504/magma-add-agw.png	{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
