iConnecting the Base Station to SAS		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iAt this point, the base station is connected to your core network, but		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
isince it hasn't connected to the CBRS SAS system (Spectrum Access		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iSystem) and obtained frequency authorization, it still won't transmit		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iLTE signals.		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iWe need to register an account with a SAS system and register our base		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
istation to obtain frequency authorization.		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iI used		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
hGoogle SAS	URL:https://cloud.google.com/products/spectrum-access-system	{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i, a SAS system run by Google Cloud. Google SAS is currently the		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
ieasiest SAS system to register with; other vendors' SAS systems		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iusually require contacting sales and signing enterprise-level service		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
icontracts to use. Moreover, Google SAS is extremely affordable; at the		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
itime of writing,		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
hthe price for indoor base stations is $2.64 per month per unit, and for outdoor base stations, it's $13.15 per month per unit	URL:https://cloud.google.com/products/spectrum-access-system#pricing	{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iYou need to register a Google Cloud account first, then visit the		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
hSAS configuration page in the console	URL:https://console.cloud.google.com/spectrum-access	{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iand follow these steps to configure:		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i- Determine your latitude and longitude. If you use an Android phone,		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iyou can download the		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
hGPS Status & Toolbox	URL:https://play.google.com/store/apps/details?id=com.eclipsim.gpsstatus2	{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iapp from Google Play to view your latitude and longitude. If you use		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
ian iPhone, you can view your latitude and longitude from the built-in		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iCompass app.		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i- In the console, select the "Add Site" button at the top (the one		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iwith a plus sign), and click anywhere on the map. A sidebar will pop		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iup on the right, asking you to enter information about your base		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
istation.		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
IGoogle SAS Add Site Button	/usr/uploads/202504/google-sas-add-button.png	{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i- First, switch to the first tab on the right sidebar (Location) and		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
ienter your correct latitude and longitude. It doesn't need to be very		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iprecise; the base station itself will upload its GPS location.		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
IGoogle SAS Enter Latitude and Longitude Interface	/usr/uploads/202504/google-sas-enter-location.png	{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i- Then, switch to the second tab (Base Station Information) and fill		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iin the following:		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i- `CBSD category` should be `A` for indoor base stations and `B` for		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
ioutdoor base stations, based on your actual situation.		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i- `FCC ID` should be the FCC ID on the base station's label.		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i- `Serial number` should be the serial number on the base station's		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
ilabel.		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i- `Device type` should be `Indoor` (indoor) or `Outdoor` (outdoor),		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
ibased on your actual situation.		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i- Under `Air Interface`, select `E_UTRA` (corresponding to LTE) for		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i`Radio technology`.		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i- Under `Antenna`, fill in `Height` with your GPS altitude.		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i- Under `Antenna`, select `Height type` as `AMSL` (height referenced		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
ito sea level).		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i- Under `Antenna`, fill in `Azimuth` with the compass direction the		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
ibase station faces.		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i- For FreedomFi/Sercomm indoor base stations, since the antenna		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
itransmits in 360 degrees, the direction doesn't matter, so you can		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
idirectly enter `0`.		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i- Under `Antenna`, fill in `Mech downtilt` with the degree of downward		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
itilt of the base station; if there's no tilt, you can directly enter		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i`0`.		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i- Under `Antenna`, fill in `Horiz accuracy` with `10`.		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i- Under `Antenna`, fill in `Vert accuracy` with `3`.		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i- You also need to fill in the following based on the base station's		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
idata sheet. If you're using a FreedomFi/Sercomm indoor base station,		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iyou can directly copy my configuration:		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i- `Max EIRP` should be `29` for FreedomFi/Sercomm indoor base		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
istations.		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i- Under `Antenna`, `Max gain` should be `5` for FreedomFi/Sercomm		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iindoor base stations.		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i- Under `Antenna`, `Beamwidth` should be `360` for FreedomFi/Sercomm		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iindoor base stations.		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i- Under `Antenna`, `Azimuth` should be `360` for FreedomFi/Sercomm		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iindoor base stations.		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i- Under `Measurement capability`, for FreedomFi/Sercomm indoor base		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
istations, do not check `RX w/ grant`, but check `RX w/o grant`.		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i- Under `Air Interface`, `Supported spec` should be `FFS` for		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iFreedomFi/Sercomm indoor base stations.		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i- You can leave the rest of the configurations blank; click `Ready for		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iCPI`.		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i- At this point, the page will display "The new configuration must be		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
isigned by a CPI before the CBSD registers with the SAS." (The base		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
istation needs to be approved by a Certified Professional Installer		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i(CPI) before it can register with the SAS again). If you're installing		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
ian indoor base station, you can ignore this. But if you're installing		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
ian outdoor base station, you'll need to find a Certified Professional		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iInstaller to approve the configuration, or		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
hspend $600 to get certified as a CPI	URL:https://www.coursera.org/learn/google-cbrs-cpi-training	{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
IGoogle SAS Base Station Information Interface 1	/usr/uploads/202504/google-sas-radio-info-1.png	{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
IGoogle SAS Base Station Information Interface 2	/usr/uploads/202504/google-sas-radio-info-2.png	{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iReboot the base station: unplug the power from your base station, wait		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
ia few seconds, then plug it back in. After a few minutes, once the		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
ibase station has started up and completed GPS positioning, the Google		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iSAS configuration page should show some yellow-highlighted `Active		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iconfig value`, indicating that these configurations differ from what		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iyou entered. You can ignore them.		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iSwitch to the `Status` tab to view the device status; you should see		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
ithe base station status as `Authorized` and the corresponding		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
ifrequency allocation.		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iAt this point, check the base station's indicator lights; the leftmost		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iLTE status indicator light should be a steady blue, indicating that		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iit's now transmitting LTE signals. This completes the base station		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iconfiguration.		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iTake out your phone, select any SIM card, turn off the "Automatic		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iNetwork Selection" option, and the phone will automatically search for		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
inearby mobile networks. If your phone supports LTE band 48, you should		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
isee a network named 315010, which is the signal transmitted by your		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
ibase station.		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iProgramming SIM Cards		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iWith the LTE network in place, the next step is to program your		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
inetwork's authentication information onto the SIM cards, allowing		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iphones to connect to your network.		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iWhen I bought the programmable SIM cards, the seller provided Windows		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
icard-programming software compatible with these SIM cards. I tried		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iusing pySim to program the cards on Linux, but the resulting SIM cards		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
icouldn't connect to the network for authentication, so I used Windows		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
ifor this step.		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iInsert the SIM card programmer into your computer and insert a		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iprogrammable SIM card into the programmer.		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iOpen the card-programming software, first click the `Read Card` button		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iin the top right to attempt to read the card's information, ensuring		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
ithe programmer is connected properly.		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iThen, in the `LTE/WCDMA Parameter` section on the right, enter the		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
ifollowing information:		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i- Select `IMSI15` and enter `3150109999XXXXX`, where the first ten		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
idigits are fixed, and the last five can be numbered arbitrarily.		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i- The first six digits `315010` are the MCC/MNC for CBRS networks.		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i- The next four digits `9999` are the IBN (IMSI Block Number) within		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
ithe CBRS network; `9999` is the test number reserved for CBRS. The		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
icomplete IBN allocation table can be found on the		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
hCBRS Assignments	URL:https://imsiadmin.com/assignments/cbrs/	{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iwebpage.		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i- The last five digits can be any number you choose.		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i- Ensure the `AD` field value is `00000003`. If it's different, click		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
ithe edit button on the right and ensure the MNC length is set to 3.		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i- In the `KI` and `OPC` fields, enter a random 32-character		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
ihexadecimal string for each. These strings are the authentication keys		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
ifor the SIM card and cannot be read back once written to the SIM card.		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i- Keep a backup of the `KI` and `OPC` values; you'll need to enter		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
ithem into the Magma core network management page later.		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i- Click the `Auto` button next to `PLMNwAct`, and the four input		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
ifields on the left should automatically fill with the values shown in		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
ithe image.		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i- Change the `SPN` to the operator name you want to display on your		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iphone, for example, `Lan Tian Mobile`.		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iFinally, click the `Write Card` button in the top right to program the		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
icard.		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iIf you want to program multiple SIM cards, follow the same process,		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
ibut ensure that the `IMSI15`, `KI`, and `OPC` values are different for		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
ieach card.		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
